The paper deals with learning manipulation skills for robots using a physics simulator and an abstract image-based representation. This involves complex interaction between multiple objects, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of a neural network to learn useful features and the ability to generalize over object shapes and numbers suggest the involvement of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computer vision (cs.CV). The paper also mentions the ability to perform look-ahead planning, which is a key aspect of control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the use of simulated and real-world experiments suggests the involvement of machine learning (cs.LG).
